*How to install an ubuntu/debian linux dev environment of Synthesis*

-To have a self-contained sandbox which doesn't interfere with your linux distribution, install virtualenv:

apt-get install python-virtualenv

-Now make a sandbox with python-virtualenv:

user@host:~/workspace/synthesis$ mkdir sandbox
user@host:~/workspace/synthesis$ virtualenv --no-site-packages --clear sandbox
New python executable in sandbox/bin/python
Installing distribute..................................................................................................................................................................................done.

-Activate your new virtualenv:
user@host:~/workspace/synthesis$ source ~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox/bin/activate
(sandbox)user@host:~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox$

-Get the code:
(sandbox)user@host:~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox$ svn co http://xsd.alexandriaconsulting.com/repos/trunk/synthesis/./code

-Prep the environment for buildout:
-Copy the 'src' directory in trunk to the 'installer/buildout/src' directory, and rename to 'synthesis'.  So this will look like: '/installer/buildout/src/synthesis/'

(sandbox)eric@ericasus:~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox/$ cd ../code
(sandbox)user@host:~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox/code$ cp -a ./src ./installer/buildout/src/
(sandbox)user@host:~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox/code$ mv ./installer/buildout/src/src ./installer/buildout/src/synthesis

-Copy the 'conf' directory in trunk to the 'installer/buildout/src/synthesis/conf' directory.  This will look like: '/installer/buildout/src/synthesis/conf/'
(sandbox)user@host:~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox/code$ cp -a ./conf ./installer/buildout/src/synthesis/

-Tweak the conf file to match your email server, address, etc.

-Now there is one fix needed:
In ./installer/buildout/buildout.cfg, in the [python] section, change 
interpreter = ${buildout:directory}/bin/
to:
interpreter = ${buildout:directory}/bin/buildout


-Then try running the './installer/install-linux.sh' script, I'd personally use the 'ignore' option for database type and use your own database or 2nd choice would be the 'os' option which will do a yum/apt and attempt to install a postgres server.

(sandbox)user@host:~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox/code/installer$ chmod a+x install-linux.sh
(sandbox)user@host:~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox/code/installer$ sudo ./install-linux.sh -f ~/workspace/synthesis/sandbox/dev_environment -d ignore -s debian

-When you're done developing in the sandbox, turn off the virtualenv:
(sandbox)user@host:~/workspace/synthesis$ deactivate


